{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535884"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:00:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:00:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15555"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15555"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.07,0.07,0.1,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62359"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8246"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47806"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8053"},{"type":"tags","id":"8790"},{"type":"tags","id":"8861"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19931"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62359"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has gastroesophageal reflux and takes occasional omeprazole. His mother died of a myocardial infarction at age 48, and his brother had a transient ischaemic attack at age 45. He smokes one pack per day since age 20, and drinks two beers on the weekend.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 15/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Eye examination reveals bilateral grey-white rings at the corneal periphery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassure and discharge","Carotid doppler ultrasound","Coronary angiogram","Ophthalmology referral","Fasting lipid profile"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with arcus senilis (corneal arcus) at a relatively young age. While arcus senilis is a common and benign finding in elderly patients, its presence in individuals under 50 years of age can be associated with underlying lipid disorders and increased cardiovascular risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasting lipid profile\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as arcus senilis in young patients is strongly associated with familial hypercholesterolaemia and other lipid disorders. This is particularly relevant given the family history of early cardiovascular death and his own cardiovascular risk factor of smoking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and discharge\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the finding of arcus senilis at this age requires further investigation. While this would be appropriate for an elderly patient, at age 42 it warrants a workup for underlying dyslipidaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOphthalmology referral\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as arcus senilis is not a primary eye condition requiring specialist management. It would not cause any symptoms and requires no treatment.  The underlying systemic condition needs to be addressed first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid doppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the first-line investigation. While patients with premature arcus senilis may have increased cardiovascular risk, initial assessment should focus on identifying the underlying lipid disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive test that would only be considered if there were symptoms or signs of coronary artery disease. It is not indicated as a screening test in this asymptomatic patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management is recognising that arcus senilis in a young person is a potential marker for underlying systemic disease, particularly disorders of lipid metabolism. The presence of a family history of early cardiovascular death further strengthens the need for investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Arcus senilis in patients under 50 years of age suggests underlying dyslipidaemia requiring investigation.","Arcus senilis in older patients is a normal age-related finding and does not require further workup."],"references":["Weinstein J, Bunya V, Ahmad S. Arcus Senilis. Eye Wiki. 2024. Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Arcus_Senilis","Hashemi H, Malekifar P, Aghamirsalim M, Yekta A, Mahboubipour H, Khabazkhoob M. Prevalence and associated factors of corneal arcus in the geriatric population; Tehran geriatric eye study. BMC Ophthalmology. 2022.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9429327/#CR10"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47806"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15555"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47806"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T17:53:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T17:53:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8246"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"